you get a powerful drawing of the creative process.

97
00:05:48,268 --> 00:05:50,528
And when you ask what's a game programmer, you get John Carmack.

98
00:05:50,848 --> 00:05:52,429
You get a specific guy.

99
00:05:52,469 --> 00:05:55,489
You get somebody sitting at a desk programming.

100
00:05:57,170 --> 00:06:00,430
And so even the general populace sort of knows

101
00:06:00,550 --> 00:06:02,451
there's a very distinct difference between the two.

102
00:06:04,268 --> 00:06:09,076
And so, the process by which these two groups actually do work is vastly different as well.

103
00:06:09,677 --> 00:06:12,241
The design, as you guys all know, is very free form.

104
00:06:12,662 --> 00:06:14,064
It's super collaborative.

105
00:06:14,625 --> 00:06:15,787
It's largely discovered.

106
00:06:16,348 --> 00:06:17,409
It's, you're kind of...

107
00:06:18,807 --> 00:06:23,069
out there in design space looking for the fun combination of rules

108
00:06:23,169 --> 00:06:25,791
that give you something special.

109
00:06:26,231 --> 00:06:28,532
And it's very situational, depending on the game,

110
00:06:28,892 --> 00:06:30,573
the part of the development process.

111
00:06:30,933 --> 00:06:35,776
There's no real sort of formula for the design process at any given moment.

112
00:06:36,897 --> 00:06:38,277
Whereas programmers are not that way.

113
00:06:39,438 --> 00:06:41,239
Typically their job is much more structured.

114
00:06:41,612 --> 00:06:46,497
they can divvy out tasks and separate systems much more easily

115
00:06:46,657 --> 00:06:48,619
and they can divvy out the work much more easily.

116
00:06:49,419 --> 00:06:51,281
They deal in abstract systems

117
00:06:52,202 --> 00:06:55,805
and that's sort of their mindset in the total.

118
00:06:56,345 --> 00:06:58,147
And also they're typically a lot more isolated.

119
00:06:59,288 --> 00:07:01,890
They tend to be able to figure out a task,

120
00:07:02,171 --> 00:07:04,753
go off and kind of do it and come back for feedback.

121
00:07:05,354 --> 00:07:06,455
That's not the case with...

122
00:07:07,748 --> 00:07:12,352
with design. Typically, you don't have that sort of back and forth. You have group, group

123
00:07:12,392 --> 00:07:15,935
sort of dynamics. So if you have a mixed team environment, you can see where this might

124
00:07:15,995 --> 00:07:22,080
rub everybody kind of the wrong way. The programmers are going to feel interrupted quite frequently

125
00:07:22,120 --> 00:07:28,024
because there's a loud, potentially boisterous talk going on right next to them. And while,

126
00:07:28,084 --> 00:07:32,568
yes, occasionally, they're going to be able to give some feedback that might steer that

127
00:07:32,628 --> 00:07:33,528
group in the right direction.

128
00:07:34,397 --> 00:07:38,118
For every one of those times, there's probably 10 times where they're going to give some

129
00:07:38,178 --> 00:07:43,680
feedback or naysay something that the designers aren't even trying to say we should do.

130
00:07:43,740 --> 00:07:48,362
They're blue-skying over here and they're bouncing stuff around and it's sort of proto-ideas.

131
00:07:48,822 --> 00:07:50,663
And you don't want to naysay a proto-idea, right?

132
00:07:50,703 --> 00:07:52,403
Because that leads to stifling.

133
00:07:52,823 --> 00:07:59,286
And on the same other side of the coin, you know, the designers might feel stifled when

134
00:07:59,446 --> 00:08:02,207
in reality they maybe just...

135
00:08:02,709 --> 00:08:05,810
are miscommunicating what they're talking about at any given time.

136
00:08:06,150 --> 00:08:10,631
And so, yeah, I think for certain parts of the development,

137
00:08:10,671 --> 00:08:12,671
a mixed team sort of environment works.

138
00:08:12,751 --> 00:08:15,431
I especially like it when you're doing a new feature.

139
00:08:16,232 --> 00:08:17,652
You all kind of sit together for a while

140
00:08:17,972 --> 00:08:20,512
and kind of get an idea as to the beginnings of it

141
00:08:20,552 --> 00:08:22,013
and the starts of it and that kind of thing.

142
00:08:22,393 --> 00:08:24,833
But then, personally, I think that it's better

143
00:08:24,893 --> 00:08:29,374
if the programmers can be isolated a little bit.

144
00:08:29,919 --> 00:08:34,863
so that they can get a little bit more of that deep focus that they need to do their job.

145
00:08:37,144 --> 00:08:40,647
The two groups have very different goals when they're making games as well.

146
00:08:40,747 --> 00:08:45,250
Design is searching for fun, and they're searching for that consistent player contract.

147
00:08:45,490 --> 00:08:50,433
They're trying to find that set of rules that they can limit the player to

148
00:08:50,453 --> 00:08:57,078
and see how effectively they can sort of maintain just that contract with the player.

149
00:08:58,279 --> 00:08:59,240
Versus the programmers.

150
00:08:59,633 --> 00:09:04,194
are looking more for performance, scalability, and maintenance of the overall product.

151
00:09:04,434 --> 00:09:07,355
They're not really talking, they're not really thinking about this particular game.

152
00:09:07,395 --> 00:09:11,756
They're thinking about code in general.

153
00:09:12,576 --> 00:09:16,197
I think both sides have simplicity on their watchword,

154
00:09:16,638 --> 00:09:18,938
but I don't know that they mean it in the same way.

155
00:09:19,858 --> 00:09:21,179
And I'll talk about that in a little while.

