165
00:10:15,083 --> 00:10:24,046
And to a certain high-level extent, you can kind of see the game that Hearthstone is supposed to be just in these pictures.

166
00:10:24,907 --> 00:10:25,627
Now I want to show you...

167
00:10:26,502 --> 00:10:29,363
the series of posters that were sitting on Bob Fitch's desk,

168
00:10:29,483 --> 00:10:30,744
the lead programmer.

169
00:10:31,124 --> 00:10:32,984
And these are the programming pillars,

170
00:10:33,605 --> 00:10:36,626
in the, seven feet away from the design pillars.

171
00:10:38,206 --> 00:10:39,066
Solve the problems you have.

172
00:10:40,187 --> 00:10:41,467
Fast doesn't mean sloppy.

173
00:10:42,928 --> 00:10:43,488
Keep it simple.

174
00:10:45,269 --> 00:10:46,069
Know how it broke.

175
00:10:47,489 --> 00:10:48,090
It better work.

176
00:10:49,190 --> 00:10:49,890
Leave no tracks.

177
00:10:50,911 --> 00:10:51,891
Play the game you're making.

178
00:10:52,391 --> 00:10:53,251
And use the right tool.

179
00:10:53,852 --> 00:10:55,672
Now, one thing you should notice on these.

180
00:10:56,725 --> 00:10:58,727
is that these have nothing to do with Hearthstone.

181
00:10:59,568 --> 00:11:03,092
In fact, these are the exact, oh excuse me,

182
00:11:03,212 --> 00:11:05,354
these are the exact programming pillars

183
00:11:05,394 --> 00:11:07,577
that Bob Fitch has used for 20 years.

184
00:11:09,559 --> 00:11:13,183
These are about building tools and about building systems

185
00:11:13,683 --> 00:11:15,865
and about working with the other programmers.

186
00:11:16,886 --> 00:11:17,467
Leave no tracks.

187
00:11:20,068 --> 00:11:27,129
And so the difference here is that one group is very much thinking about the game and what it means to make this game,

188
00:11:27,669 --> 00:11:33,211
whereas the other group is very much interested in the process and what it means to do the process.

189
00:11:35,111 --> 00:11:40,192
Now, how do these different goals and motivations lead to success?

190
00:11:40,712 --> 00:11:47,713
What is it about performing these goals and motivations that actually give satisfaction down the road?

191
00:11:48,484 --> 00:11:51,805
to these groups. I mean, obviously you can tell they're fairly different, right?

192
00:11:51,945 --> 00:12:00,529
For the designers, fun is fun, right? But if you can maintain a contract and maintain

193
00:12:00,589 --> 00:12:04,250
simplicity, you're talking about that game that's easy to pick up and difficult to master.

194
00:12:04,590 --> 00:12:09,052
You've made an accessible game that a lot of people can learn that rule set and really

195
00:12:09,512 --> 00:12:14,414
dive into. Whereas the programmers, they've won if they've kept the bug count low.

196
00:12:15,067 --> 00:12:19,890
if they've made intuitive code so that an additional staff that comes in can jump in

197
00:12:20,130 --> 00:12:28,175
and help out, and if there's no crunch. That's how they win. And so you can see where sometimes

198
00:12:28,795 --> 00:12:34,378
something that the designers want that will actually give them the win is exactly the

199
00:12:34,418 --> 00:12:38,641
thing that might cause the programmers to lose what they consider to be the win. And

200
00:12:38,741 --> 00:12:40,962
that's a big source of rub, right?

201
00:12:44,355 --> 00:12:49,699
the common thread for the two to win is the word elegance.

202
00:12:50,740 --> 00:12:52,901
But even then I think they're thinking about it in two different ways.

203
00:12:52,941 --> 00:12:56,964
I think when you have an elegant game, that's where you have the minimum set of rules

204
00:12:58,506 --> 00:12:59,927
so that you have depth in your game,

205
00:13:00,207 --> 00:13:02,949
but it's not so many rules that it's complex.

206
00:13:03,029 --> 00:13:04,070
It's accessible still.

207
00:13:04,390 --> 00:13:06,812
Whereas in programming, elegance means

208
00:13:08,913 --> 00:13:11,035
it means the code is clever,

209
00:13:11,435 --> 00:13:13,016
but not in an unintuitive way, again.

210
00:13:13,339 --> 00:13:19,485
because that's a strength. But it's clever in such that you get a surprising jump in

211
00:13:19,545 --> 00:13:24,290
performance or a surprising jump in optimization of space or something. And so when the programmers

212
00:13:24,330 --> 00:13:29,635
say elegance, they mean the code itself is elegant, not the game, which is what the designers

213
00:13:29,675 --> 00:13:32,918
are talking about. Again, there's sort of a different tack.

214
00:13:34,119 --> 00:13:38,063
So how do we get these two groups to work together? They're very different people.

215
00:13:38,674 --> 00:13:40,815
And they have to be very closely associated.

216
00:13:40,835 --> 00:13:41,756
And how do we do this?

217
00:13:42,156 --> 00:13:44,337
I think for me, it's all about beginnings.

218
00:13:45,098 --> 00:13:48,400
It's all about when your game first starts, especially with

219
00:13:48,440 --> 00:13:54,524
new staff, you have, I like to use a two-part process to sort

220
00:13:54,544 --> 00:13:57,406
of jumpstart the process of this connection.

221
00:13:58,507 --> 00:14:00,228
First, I like to call it the pre-prototype.

222
00:14:00,949 --> 00:14:03,730
When the design has been gone on long enough, you've got a

223
00:14:03,790 --> 00:14:04,971
nice paper prototype.

224
00:14:04,991 --> 00:14:07,113
You've got a good idea of the rule sets.

225
00:14:08,240 --> 00:14:10,760
That's when you bring the designer in, or excuse me, the programmer in.

226
00:14:12,040 --> 00:14:17,642
And that way you can get everybody on board and on the same page as to what the design is going to be.

227
00:14:18,002 --> 00:14:19,562
You can start the buy-in process.

228
00:14:20,022 --> 00:14:26,603
And more importantly, you can actually, at this point, essentially teach the programmer how your brain works.

229
00:14:27,483 --> 00:14:35,585
How you perceive this design problem, how you perceive what are the important bits and what are sort of not the important bits.

230
00:14:35,705 --> 00:14:36,125
All of that.

231
00:14:38,189 --> 00:14:43,693
this is your time to sort of shine and give him insight into your brain.

232
00:14:45,634 --> 00:14:48,877
I like to do this with as many different types of media as I can.

233
00:14:48,917 --> 00:14:50,598
The paper prototypes work great.

234
00:14:51,699 --> 00:14:54,000
Obviously talking, doing a lot of whiteboarding.

235
00:14:55,801 --> 00:14:56,342
Act it out.

236
00:14:57,302 --> 00:15:00,464
Stand next to each other and act it out if that would make it more clear.

237
00:15:00,945 --> 00:15:04,307
Human beings have a lot of different ways of retaining information and sometimes...

238
00:15:04,788 --> 00:15:08,269
you can give an email to somebody and they will remember it for 10 years and other times

239
00:15:08,709 --> 00:15:13,150
you can give somebody a piece of paper and they will read it 20 times and they will still

240
00:15:13,170 --> 00:15:15,450
have to pick it up for that 21st time.

241
00:15:15,530 --> 00:15:16,910
They will never, it will never stick.

242
00:15:17,330 --> 00:15:20,531
And so mixed media is super important.

243
00:15:20,551 --> 00:15:23,232
I mean, any grade school teacher will tell you this, right?

244
00:15:24,672 --> 00:15:25,972
People learn in different ways.

245
00:15:28,133 --> 00:15:31,993
And the purpose of this...

246
00:15:33,950 --> 00:15:38,713
interview, if you will, is to explore the boundaries of your game space with the programmer

247
00:15:38,833 --> 00:15:45,436
right from the start. It gives him the opportunity to push back on your design, try and find

248
00:15:45,496 --> 00:15:51,400
exceptions and edge cases. And it gives you the opportunity to explain how the design

249
00:15:51,460 --> 00:15:57,743
encompasses those edge cases and those exceptions. Because at this point, he's trying to determine

250
00:15:57,783 --> 00:16:02,666
an abstraction that's going to work well to encode your game design. And at the same

251
00:16:02,706 --> 00:16:02,946
time...

252
00:16:03,792 --> 00:16:06,993
those exceptions, those edge cases might be things you haven't thought of. And so it's

253
00:16:07,013 --> 00:16:12,455
going to give you clarity in forcing you to verbalize those things to the programmer.

254
00:16:13,835 --> 00:16:21,018
So then he's going to go off, or they, they're going to go off and do the code. And they're

255
00:16:21,038 --> 00:16:23,678
going to come back to you at some point with some semblance of a prototype.

256
00:16:27,172 --> 00:16:29,733
the, the, it's, it's, it's time for the opposite to happen.

257
00:16:30,113 --> 00:16:33,995
Now, it's your turn, as a designer, to get into his head,

258
00:16:34,596 --> 00:16:37,377
and to see if he got the message, as well as,

259
00:16:37,517 --> 00:16:38,998
as well as how he thinks about things.

260
00:16:39,419 --> 00:16:41,340
So now it's time for you to push back on,

261
00:16:41,520 --> 00:16:44,641
on his abstraction, and let him explain how his system

262
00:16:44,681 --> 00:16:47,863
is going to encompass, I keep saying his, I apologize,

263
00:16:48,123 --> 00:16:51,685
how the programmer is going to encompass your, your,

264
00:16:53,106 --> 00:16:53,586
your design.

265
00:16:54,029 --> 00:16:57,170
how his abstraction is going to handle everything that it needs to handle.

266
00:16:57,610 --> 00:17:03,291
And again, the same thing happens when you work on exceptions and what have you.

267
00:17:05,031 --> 00:17:12,072
The programmer clarifying these things in his own mind while they talk about it

268
00:17:12,253 --> 00:17:13,773
is a very important step.

269
00:17:13,793 --> 00:17:17,173
Part of the reason I'm tripping so hard is because

270
00:17:17,694 --> 00:17:20,414
the female programmer from Hearthstone is right here and I'm trying not to be a jerk.

271
00:17:24,206 --> 00:17:29,248
He also has a, they also have a lot more idea about the performance of the system.

272
00:17:29,328 --> 00:17:34,110
How the system is going to play out given all of the things that now, now are known

273
00:17:34,390 --> 00:17:37,292
about the program and how it's going to handle data.

274
00:17:38,352 --> 00:17:44,895
And so, this is where the programmer might give you a, a, hey, if you don't have to do

275
00:17:44,955 --> 00:17:46,616
this all the time, it would be a good thing.

276
00:17:46,676 --> 00:17:50,037
In fact, let's make some limitations and some budgeting based on performance numbers that

277
00:17:50,057 --> 00:17:50,358
we already know.

278
00:17:50,378 --> 00:17:51,478
And if, if it doesn't work, it's not going to work.

279
00:17:51,498 --> 00:17:52,178
It's not going to work.

280
00:17:52,897 --> 00:17:58,219
this is a really good time to sort of start the negotiation process for the interaction

281
00:17:58,259 --> 00:18:06,942
between the two camps. Again, it's good for you as a designer to watch out for over-engineering.

282
00:18:08,243 --> 00:18:13,505
The programmer might be making a system that's way too broad to try and grab every possible

283
00:18:13,605 --> 00:18:18,067
option. And if you notice this and you say, hey, hey, that's really never going to happen,

284
00:18:19,267 --> 00:18:21,448
you can give the programmer

285
00:18:22,870 --> 00:18:26,051
boundaries that you're willing to live with such that he might be able to

286
00:18:27,571 --> 00:18:28,611
simplify things down at

287
00:18:30,532 --> 00:18:34,893
at the system level and actually get some real good gains and

288
00:18:35,433 --> 00:18:40,714
again, they'll watch out for trust fails at this point because if you say something's never gonna happen and then down the road you say

289
00:18:42,515 --> 00:18:44,595
Yeah, we're gonna do that now like that

290
00:18:44,635 --> 00:18:48,156
That's a big problem and be prepared for some sort of strong

291
00:18:48,216 --> 00:18:51,957
Negotiations because this is very early in the process and if you say never at that point

292
00:18:52,496 --> 00:18:53,597
You better kind of mean it.

293
00:18:55,618 --> 00:18:58,240
So what I'm talking about here is establishing a connection

294
00:18:58,260 --> 00:18:59,320
between two human beings.

295
00:18:59,380 --> 00:19:02,222
And this is the standard metaphor, right?

296
00:19:02,262 --> 00:19:04,924
Because, yeah, two human beings can link up.

297
00:19:04,964 --> 00:19:07,506
There is an easy way to even communicate.

298
00:19:07,546 --> 00:19:08,526
But there is signal loss.

299
00:19:09,607 --> 00:19:12,409
The problem I have with this particular hookup

300
00:19:12,909 --> 00:19:14,310
is that it's typically more like this.

301
00:19:14,970 --> 00:19:15,411
These are not.

302
00:19:17,022 --> 00:19:20,745
people that really speak the same language or think the same way.

303
00:19:21,145 --> 00:19:23,987
And so you really have to come about it in this way instead.

304
00:19:25,969 --> 00:19:30,373
A lot of programming is more top-down and content is more bottom-up.

305
00:19:31,273 --> 00:19:37,659
I think a lot of systems designers also think top-down and so there is some common ground,

306
00:19:37,699 --> 00:19:43,143
but it's a really hard road to do and you really have to be careful and you really should

307
00:19:43,163 --> 00:19:45,765
start thinking about things in these terms so that you don't...

308
00:19:47,987 --> 00:19:50,328
Designers love to use flowery language.

309
00:19:50,648 --> 00:19:54,089
We hate seeing the same word used over and over again.

310
00:19:54,509 --> 00:20:00,451
But programmers basically love clarity of language.

311
00:20:01,232 --> 00:20:03,252
It's actually probably one of the reasons why we deal with

312
00:20:03,292 --> 00:20:05,813
computers better than people.

313
00:20:06,133 --> 00:20:08,934
Because computers, by definition, are the ultimate

314
00:20:08,974 --> 00:20:09,955
example of clear.

315
00:20:10,424 --> 00:20:14,767
clear language. You know, every time you put a semicolon in the wrong spot, the computer

316
00:20:14,807 --> 00:20:18,690
will say, wrong. And that starts to sort of sound like a lot of programmers, doesn't it?

317
00:20:18,730 --> 00:20:24,615
You know, like you, you, you, you deal with that entity enough in your life and you, you

318
00:20:24,655 --> 00:20:28,618
will become that, you know, like they, they will tell you when you put the semicolon in

319
00:20:28,658 --> 00:20:34,103
the wrong point. And so, what we really need to do to establish this connection is, is

320
00:20:34,143 --> 00:20:36,205
remember that communication clarity is key.

321
00:20:36,708 --> 00:20:43,150
Vocabulary is actually one of the very few things that human beings do when they form groups to bond.

322
00:20:44,470 --> 00:20:48,511
High school cliques are about forming your own vocabulary.

323
00:20:50,952 --> 00:20:57,973
Human beings do this so that they can feel a kinship with each other and know that they're on the same page.

324
00:20:58,213 --> 00:21:03,694
It's one of the reasons why when geeks get together and we start quoting movies, we feel more connected to each other.

325
00:21:03,734 --> 00:21:05,695
It's because that's our shared vocabulary.

326
00:21:06,615 --> 00:21:09,196
And if you have that one friend in your group that keeps

327
00:21:11,137 --> 00:21:13,998
quoting Monty Python wrong or slightly wrong,

328
00:21:15,379 --> 00:21:16,079
he doesn't get it.

329
00:21:17,060 --> 00:21:18,360
He's never going to be in the group.

330
00:21:18,720 --> 00:21:19,761
Nobody likes that guy.

331
00:21:21,722 --> 00:21:24,043
And so when you're dealing with programmers,

332
00:21:24,063 --> 00:21:25,384
you really have to remember that

333
00:21:25,704 --> 00:21:29,125
they are the kings of consistent and clear language

334
00:21:29,225 --> 00:21:31,626
because that's what the computer demands of them.

335
00:21:32,167 --> 00:21:34,588
And the more senior a guy is, I think that...

336
00:21:35,346 --> 00:21:38,108
he can get a little wiggle room and he can figure things out.

337
00:21:38,488 --> 00:21:42,491
But the junior a person is, they're still very fresh.

338
00:21:42,611 --> 00:21:45,193
Every time the computer's slapped them, it's still like

339
00:21:45,293 --> 00:21:46,374
stinging on their cheek.

340
00:21:46,814 --> 00:21:49,056
And so they're still in that mode.

341
00:21:49,276 --> 00:21:51,317
And when they come in and they talk to the designers,

342
00:21:51,757 --> 00:21:53,339
sometimes they want to sting you back.

343
00:21:54,459 --> 00:21:57,922
I've seen entire meetings be derailed by a single antonym.

344
00:21:58,642 --> 00:22:01,304
Some designer in the room will say the word actor when he

345
00:22:01,344 --> 00:22:02,085
meant entity.

346
00:22:03,771 --> 00:22:05,173
Some programmer will go, wait, wait, wait.

347
00:22:05,393 --> 00:22:07,675
Are you talking about the entity?

348
00:22:07,695 --> 00:22:09,236
Or are you talking about the battle manager?

349
00:22:10,057 --> 00:22:11,718
And his brain is off in that direction now,

350
00:22:11,798 --> 00:22:13,359
trying to find the inconsistency.

351
00:22:13,640 --> 00:22:15,121
It's no longer in the meeting.

352
00:22:15,561 --> 00:22:18,584
And you have to practically apologize to the guy.

353
00:22:18,624 --> 00:22:21,046
No, no, no. I'm sorry. I said the wrong thing.

354
00:22:21,506 --> 00:22:23,168
And that's annoying. I agree.

355
00:22:24,028 --> 00:22:26,911
But it's something you should be aware is happening.

356
00:22:27,571 --> 00:22:29,653
Consistency of vocabulary is something

357
00:22:29,673 --> 00:22:32,355
that really needs to be set up in that pre-production phase.

358
00:22:32,768 --> 00:22:34,769
where you set a vocabulary for the game.

359
00:22:35,190 --> 00:22:38,451
And hopefully he'll code the thing using the same vocabulary

360
00:22:38,471 --> 00:22:41,313
so that when you talk, the consistency stays.

361
00:22:42,293 --> 00:22:44,794
Now, during the prototype phase, he's going to come back at you

362
00:22:44,834 --> 00:22:46,515
with some naming systems that he's made up.

363
00:22:46,975 --> 00:22:48,596
Maybe there's a scripting language,

364
00:22:48,896 --> 00:22:50,757
and he's written out a bunch of opcodes.

365
00:22:50,797 --> 00:22:54,879
Or maybe there's a naming system for the assets

366
00:22:54,899 --> 00:22:56,200
that are going to be loaded into the game.

367
00:22:57,053 --> 00:23:00,775
I personally as a programmer try to have some flexibility in this.

368
00:23:01,075 --> 00:23:06,396
In the Hearthstone game, I first brought the list of opcodes for the scripting system to

369
00:23:07,196 --> 00:23:11,038
the designer and they were all written in a third person.

370
00:23:11,338 --> 00:23:14,559
Like the player who owns this card was an opcode.

371
00:23:14,999 --> 00:23:18,400
So that in the script you could reference the player who owns this particular card in

372
00:23:18,440 --> 00:23:18,880
that script.

373
00:23:19,880 --> 00:23:24,561
And the designer at the time said, oh, I don't think about it like that.

374
00:23:25,182 --> 00:23:26,923
that's weird, I don't understand that.

375
00:23:27,763 --> 00:23:29,704
And so I said, okay, take this file.

376
00:23:30,125 --> 00:23:31,945
And there was a file with all of the opcodes

377
00:23:31,985 --> 00:23:34,747
that was read in by both the tool and the engine,

378
00:23:35,167 --> 00:23:39,389
and that was sort of the text of the opcodes

379
00:23:39,409 --> 00:23:40,309
that was used in the tools,

380
00:23:40,329 --> 00:23:41,890
because I didn't really care what they were.

381
00:23:41,910 --> 00:23:44,651
And he went through and rewrote them,

382
00:23:44,711 --> 00:23:45,792
and I looked at them afterwards,

383
00:23:46,072 --> 00:23:47,993
and what he had done was change them all

384
00:23:48,013 --> 00:23:49,473
from third person to first person.

385
00:23:49,794 --> 00:23:51,434
Because when he was writing the cards,

386
00:23:51,835 --> 00:23:54,616
he saw the script as being the card itself.

387
00:23:56,005 --> 00:24:02,669
saying what it was. So he changed the player who owns this card to my player. And I saw

388
00:24:02,709 --> 00:24:06,911
that pretty quickly and I got a good insight into his mind as to why he was reordering

389
00:24:06,931 --> 00:24:12,134
these. Okay, when he writes a script, he becomes the card and he writes my script, basically.

390
00:24:12,554 --> 00:24:17,436
And so it was very easy for me then, when I would talk to him, to use better metaphors

391
00:24:17,816 --> 00:24:20,638
to sort of get into his mode when we talked.

392
00:24:23,448 --> 00:24:26,409
However, be explicit. Again, this is a clarity issue, right?

393
00:24:27,469 --> 00:24:30,450
And there's certain things that you really have to be explicit about.

394
00:24:30,830 --> 00:24:34,091
One is priorities. Must-haves versus would-be-nice,

395
00:24:34,451 --> 00:24:38,712
that's at the bare minimum. I better know which ones you have to have

396
00:24:38,812 --> 00:24:41,713
and which ones would be nice. I mean, obviously, there's a priority of the

397
00:24:41,773 --> 00:24:42,813
would-be-nices as well.

398
00:24:43,213 --> 00:24:46,674
But post-ship is not a good priority to say.

399
00:24:47,721 --> 00:24:49,983
I want to know if it's a must-have post-ship

400
00:24:50,403 --> 00:24:52,265
or if it's a would-be-nice post-ship.

401
00:24:52,305 --> 00:24:53,406
Because if it's a must-have,

402
00:24:53,706 --> 00:24:55,588
then it might not be a post-ship feature.

403
00:24:55,688 --> 00:24:57,689
I have to take that into account as a programmer

404
00:24:58,030 --> 00:24:59,071
before the game ships.

405
00:25:00,212 --> 00:25:01,653
Otherwise, there's a nasty surprise.

406
00:25:02,033 --> 00:25:04,695
Especially if you want to do some content fairly soon after we ship.

407
00:25:05,316 --> 00:25:07,718
Estimates are another big thing that you have to be explicit about.

408
00:25:08,018 --> 00:25:09,059
Don't give snap estimates.

409
00:25:09,359 --> 00:25:12,462
Because programmers are notorious for remembering them forever.

410
00:25:14,640 --> 00:25:17,241
Ranges are a lot better as well because they show certainty.

411
00:25:17,721 --> 00:25:20,483
If I say a task is going to take me between 15 and 20 minutes,

412
00:25:21,143 --> 00:25:22,564
I think you're fairly certain about that.

413
00:25:22,584 --> 00:25:24,465
Whereas if you say it's going to take between one and four

414
00:25:24,485 --> 00:25:26,886
days, I'm going to realize immediately

415
00:25:26,966 --> 00:25:29,548
that maybe the thing I'm asking you isn't very clear.

416
00:25:30,028 --> 00:25:35,051
Because if you can't tell me within 400% time scale,

417
00:25:35,111 --> 00:25:37,332
then maybe I haven't been clear and I

418
00:25:37,372 --> 00:25:38,913
need to talk to you more about what's going on.

419
00:25:40,473 --> 00:25:42,174
There's a lot of other types of communication

420
00:25:42,194 --> 00:25:43,235
that come up in game dev.

421
00:25:43,695 --> 00:25:44,015
Meetings.

422
00:25:44,448 --> 00:25:45,169
Meetings are a big one.

423
00:25:45,489 --> 00:25:46,189
They run...

424
00:25:47,990 --> 00:25:49,831
They run nasty for most programmers.

425
00:25:50,892 --> 00:25:53,293
I think designers have a little bit better time with them.

426
00:25:53,333 --> 00:25:55,154
I think producers have the best time with them.

427
00:25:55,234 --> 00:25:58,995
I think producers actually, you know, have a bed made out of meetings at home.

428
00:26:01,257 --> 00:26:07,440
And the big reason is that the chunk size of work between the two groups is wildly different.

429
00:26:07,800 --> 00:26:09,140
I think it might be the same,

430
00:26:09,621 --> 00:26:11,602
except that programmers tend to have...

431
00:26:12,319 --> 00:26:17,305
a lead in phase and a lead out phase because your brain requires a different degree of

432
00:26:17,406 --> 00:26:22,832
focus as well as like width of information that you need to sort of have in your head

433
00:26:22,872 --> 00:26:29,140
at once in order to do a software engineering task than a collaborative creative task.

434
00:26:32,375 --> 00:26:37,880
the sort of well-documented programmer works chunk size is about four hours.

435
00:26:38,540 --> 00:26:41,583
And so if you have a meeting in the morning,

436
00:26:42,103 --> 00:26:44,305
that might actually kind of shoot the programmer's morning.

437
00:26:44,926 --> 00:26:47,288
And if you then put another meeting in the middle of the afternoon,

438
00:26:48,409 --> 00:26:48,609
ouch.

439
00:26:49,289 --> 00:26:51,611
He might not actually get that much done,

440
00:26:51,691 --> 00:26:54,154
especially high-focus work that day.

441
00:26:55,955 --> 00:26:57,376
This is one of the reasons why

442
00:26:58,448 --> 00:27:03,433
You really need to think about meetings and if they're necessary, try and front load them.

443
00:27:03,933 --> 00:27:04,854
All those sorts of issues.

444
00:27:06,035 --> 00:27:07,016
Also social setting.

445
00:27:07,396 --> 00:27:10,639
Programmers again, you know, they vary greatly.

446
00:27:12,280 --> 00:27:17,345
But in general, they're not as social as designers.

447
00:27:17,465 --> 00:27:22,609
Even here at GDC, I have people come up to me and I'm also another programmer and I can

448
00:27:22,669 --> 00:27:26,493
tell you within three words if they're a programmer or a designer.

449
00:27:27,406 --> 00:27:30,487
That's typically just eye gaze is all it takes.

450
00:27:31,368 --> 00:27:32,629
The programmer will walk up to you and go,

451
00:27:32,869 --> 00:27:33,329
hey Brian.

452
00:27:34,690 --> 00:27:37,791
And that's pretty high percentage of the time.

453
00:27:39,132 --> 00:27:40,372
They typically don't like being made

454
00:27:40,392 --> 00:27:41,193
the center of attention.

455
00:27:41,913 --> 00:27:43,894
And meetings can do that.

456
00:27:44,234 --> 00:27:46,275
I mean, I've seen the single most powerful,

457
00:27:46,535 --> 00:27:48,676
confident programmer I've ever met, practically,

458
00:27:48,956 --> 00:27:50,517
turn into one of these in a meeting.

459
00:27:50,597 --> 00:27:51,218
Hey, hey, hey, hey.

460
00:27:51,658 --> 00:27:54,499
Defensive, wants people to stop talking.

461
00:27:57,324 --> 00:28:00,065
Ongoing communications are very different as well.

462
00:28:00,665 --> 00:28:03,945
You really should, I like to do it at the start of a team.

463
00:28:04,326 --> 00:28:06,426
I like to say, hey, do you like emails?

464
00:28:06,486 --> 00:28:07,286
Do you like IMs?

465
00:28:07,586 --> 00:28:09,587
Do you want me to come talk to you in person?

466
00:28:10,267 --> 00:28:11,127
Do you like phone calls?

467
00:28:11,427 --> 00:28:13,327
Because different people like different things.

468
00:28:13,668 --> 00:28:18,168
And with programmers especially, because of that work chunk I was talking about, there's

469
00:28:18,229 --> 00:28:19,769
times of day where this might be varied.

470
00:28:20,689 --> 00:28:24,730
They might say, after 4 o'clock, please don't come anywhere near my desk.

471
00:28:24,750 --> 00:28:25,430
Send me an email.

472
00:28:25,450 --> 00:28:25,950
I'm busy.

473
00:28:25,970 --> 00:28:26,310
I'm busy.

474
00:28:26,330 --> 00:28:26,750
I'm busy.

475
00:28:27,406 --> 00:28:29,727
and that might change over the course of the project.

476
00:28:29,747 --> 00:28:32,929
But this is something that you really should think about

477
00:28:33,269 --> 00:28:36,912
because this is the sort of thing that you can really kill productivity

478
00:28:38,092 --> 00:28:39,133
completely innocuously.

479
00:28:41,114 --> 00:28:43,055
And the last thing is feedback and suggestions.

480
00:28:44,496 --> 00:28:49,959
I find that if, as a designer, you open an idea zone,

481
00:28:50,479 --> 00:28:52,821
that it makes it reciprocal,

482
00:28:53,181 --> 00:28:55,542
it makes it easier to reciprocate as a programmer.

483
00:28:55,582 --> 00:28:56,303
They will also...

484
00:28:56,911 --> 00:28:59,752
be a little bit more open for ideas when the designer comes to them.

485
00:29:01,792 --> 00:29:04,973
I love this question. This is something that Eric Dodds taught me.

486
00:29:05,753 --> 00:29:09,974
I had sort of a notion of this, but this is the most wonderful question there is, right?

487
00:29:10,414 --> 00:29:13,775
When somebody comes to you with some feedback or a suggestion,

488
00:29:14,175 --> 00:29:16,316
and they start to say, hey, you know, it'd be really cool.

489
00:29:17,036 --> 00:29:21,177
Don't say, we don't have time for that. Oh, I don't agree with that.

490
00:29:21,357 --> 00:29:23,197
There's a million different ways to answer this question.

491
00:29:24,178 --> 00:29:26,079
But this one, what are you trying to fix?

492
00:29:26,679 --> 00:29:27,419
It does two things.

493
00:29:28,040 --> 00:29:30,701
It shows respect for the person that's coming up to you with feedback.

494
00:29:31,181 --> 00:29:32,602
Because it doesn't say,

495
00:29:33,282 --> 00:29:34,203
your idea is dumb.

496
00:29:34,363 --> 00:29:34,723
It says,

497
00:29:35,843 --> 00:29:36,924
whatever your idea is,

498
00:29:36,944 --> 00:29:38,985
your intent coming up to me

499
00:29:39,225 --> 00:29:41,206
is to try and make this game better, and I see that.

500
00:29:42,466 --> 00:29:46,348
But it also potentially digs deeper than just their little description

501
00:29:46,528 --> 00:29:48,089
and gives you an idea as to what...

502
00:29:49,176 --> 00:29:51,697
the higher level thing is that they're maybe trying to fix

503
00:29:51,737 --> 00:29:52,837
and maybe there is something there.

504
00:29:52,977 --> 00:29:54,298
Maybe their idea is stupid,

505
00:29:54,558 --> 00:29:57,599
but maybe the thing that they're trying to fix is not non-existent.

506
00:30:00,100 --> 00:30:00,960
Other communication.

507
00:30:01,441 --> 00:30:04,121
Documentation is a sore spot.

508
00:30:04,562 --> 00:30:05,882
I mean, I don't know that

509
00:30:07,463 --> 00:30:10,164
programmers do documentation all that much better,

510
00:30:10,704 --> 00:30:14,205
but we definitely try because we make it part of our process.

511
00:30:15,515 --> 00:30:21,079
And I think designers try as well, but they tend to, especially later in the project,

512
00:30:21,359 --> 00:30:24,281
kind of fall off the wagon a little bit more than programmers do.

513
00:30:25,201 --> 00:30:29,284
So try and keep your design docs up to date, especially if they're short.

514
00:30:29,584 --> 00:30:30,765
Keep your design docs short.

515
00:30:34,308 --> 00:30:39,371
Our Hearthstone designer was proud of himself because he could get our documentation down

516
00:30:39,411 --> 00:30:40,372
to about two pages.

517
00:30:40,972 --> 00:30:43,674
And that was a point of pride with him.

518
00:30:44,327 --> 00:30:47,190
And I applauded him for it when he did it because that takes work.

519
00:30:47,550 --> 00:30:52,514
You know, I've made GDC talks take less and less slides

520
00:30:52,554 --> 00:30:55,176
and that's a really hard thing to do to boil something down.

521
00:30:57,358 --> 00:31:00,661
When we talk about design-driven production,

522
00:31:01,241 --> 00:31:04,644
the information about how to make this game

523
00:31:04,724 --> 00:31:06,585
and about where the intelligence lies

524
00:31:06,725 --> 00:31:08,767
is sometimes spread out in 15 different places.

525
00:31:09,372 --> 00:31:10,753
How do I make a new actor?

526
00:31:10,813 --> 00:31:13,734
How do I make a new script for this particular actor?

527
00:31:13,795 --> 00:31:18,077
How do I, what do the priorities on the animations even mean?

528
00:31:18,457 --> 00:31:20,438
All of these sort of process level things

529
00:31:20,858 --> 00:31:22,619
need to be documented as well.

530
00:31:22,699 --> 00:31:24,500
And a lot of times this stuff falls through the cracks.

531
00:31:24,540 --> 00:31:25,841
And so you hire a new designer,

532
00:31:26,121 --> 00:31:28,682
or you hire a new programmer, and he doesn't know squat.

533
00:31:28,742 --> 00:31:32,024
And it's really hard to get these things to keep going.

534
00:31:32,904 --> 00:31:34,345
And finally, content and scripts.

535
00:31:34,865 --> 00:31:36,946
In much the same way that programmers,

536
00:31:39,099 --> 00:31:41,880
When I work with programmers, I try to get them to comment their code.

537
00:31:41,960 --> 00:31:43,080
If I look at it and I say,

538
00:31:43,120 --> 00:31:44,741
hey, this doesn't make sense to me,

539
00:31:45,041 --> 00:31:47,942
throw a comment in here so that a month from now we know what this means.

540
00:31:48,442 --> 00:31:49,923
When there's a bug.

541
00:31:50,783 --> 00:31:52,523
I do the same thing with contents and scripts.

542
00:31:53,304 --> 00:31:57,745
I put comment opcodes into my scripting languages,

543
00:31:58,185 --> 00:32:00,826
and when the designer goes to check something in,

544
00:32:00,926 --> 00:32:03,047
I say, what does this even mean?

545
00:32:03,507 --> 00:32:05,207
Throw a comment here and tell me what this means.

546
00:32:05,267 --> 00:32:08,268
The same exact statement as the programmer.

547
00:32:09,380 --> 00:32:10,940
it will help down the road.

548
00:32:11,420 --> 00:32:14,181
And it will also make that communication more clear

549
00:32:14,341 --> 00:32:18,603
so both sides can see that things are sort of even.

550
00:32:20,203 --> 00:32:21,443
Bug reports is kind of a big one,

551
00:32:21,804 --> 00:32:29,206
because obviously your designers aren't going to be doing real bug reports.

552
00:32:29,526 --> 00:32:33,607
However, they get the pre-pre-pre-pre-alpha of the game.

553
00:32:34,107 --> 00:32:37,948
And they essentially are the testers of the pre-pre-pre-crap-alpha of the game.

554
00:32:39,029 --> 00:32:41,409
And not only that, they're the pre-pre-pre-alpha of the tools.

555
00:32:42,169 --> 00:32:45,990
And so, they end up being bug reporters in a certain way.

556
00:32:46,290 --> 00:32:51,911
And so, try to know that this statement is sucky.

557
00:32:53,071 --> 00:32:55,352
We had a designer on Hearthstone that would love to say this.

558
00:32:55,732 --> 00:32:58,413
And to a certain extent, he was very systemic with this.

559
00:32:58,473 --> 00:33:00,173
He would do this to everything.

560
00:33:00,213 --> 00:33:02,653
If it was his favorite hamburger, he would say,

561
00:33:02,713 --> 00:33:05,254
This hamburger is the greatest hamburger ever!

562
00:33:06,293 --> 00:33:09,995
And we used to tease him, we used to say he was a Sith, because only Sith speak in absolutes.

563
00:33:10,936 --> 00:33:19,320
And the problem is that what this statement gives you is a notion that he doesn't feel that...

564
00:33:19,441 --> 00:33:25,804
He kind of feels like this bug sucks and it just needs to go away.

565
00:33:26,645 --> 00:33:29,146
When in reality, yeah, of course it does.

566
00:33:29,426 --> 00:33:32,908
But I need more information if I'm going to do it quickly.

567
00:33:36,077 --> 00:33:42,039
by not having legitimate bug reports and by not sort of being a part of the bug fixing

568
00:33:42,079 --> 00:33:48,282
process, it tends to build that us or them sort of thing. When in reality, it's a cooperation.

569
00:33:48,682 --> 00:33:52,543
It's two people working together to try and make the same thing. It's not an us or them.

570
00:33:55,264 --> 00:34:01,546
There's some trouble spots, obviously. Workflow, again, when you're dealing with a lot of tools,

571
00:34:05,008 --> 00:34:05,688
a lot of people get...

572
00:34:06,385 --> 00:34:09,807
very early on tools, and they start working with them, and they try to make what they can.

573
00:34:10,368 --> 00:34:11,869
And there's problems. There always will be.

574
00:34:12,730 --> 00:34:13,711
But they try to make do.

575
00:34:14,291 --> 00:34:17,934
They try to work around the bug, and they try to use the tool anyway.

576
00:34:18,214 --> 00:34:20,556
And a lot of times they do that because there's not time to fix them,

577
00:34:20,856 --> 00:34:22,898
but a lot of times they just do it because human beings

578
00:34:23,939 --> 00:34:26,681
will throw a little duct tape on the hammer and use it anyway.

579
00:34:27,842 --> 00:34:29,523
We're sort of trained to kind of make do.

580
00:34:30,604 --> 00:34:32,766
But my point is, don't do this.

581
00:34:33,597 --> 00:34:37,940
try to tell personal preferences and pet peeves on the current tool sets to your programmers

582
00:34:38,241 --> 00:34:43,185
as quickly as you can, as nicely as you can, but as quickly as you can, because if they

583
00:34:43,225 --> 00:34:48,869
can improve some of these very basic usability problems with tools and with your workflow,

584
00:34:49,570 --> 00:34:54,774
it's going to not only increase your productivity, but it's going to eliminate this nasty little

585
00:34:55,475 --> 00:34:59,518
erosion of goodwill between the programmer and the designer.

586
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:01,800
This is sort of like...

587
00:35:02,275 --> 00:35:05,878
if you're in a relationship with another human being

588
00:35:06,818 --> 00:35:09,761
and let's say that person

589
00:35:10,161 --> 00:35:13,264
doesn't lift the lid or doesn't put it down when they're done

590
00:35:14,064 --> 00:35:16,967
it's not a big thing but eventually you hate them

591
00:35:19,669 --> 00:35:20,810
so if you just tell them

592
00:35:21,050 --> 00:35:24,092
hey this is a pet peeve of mine could you please

593
00:35:24,773 --> 00:35:27,255
and if they're reasonable human being they will go

594
00:35:27,695 --> 00:35:29,937
well I could care less I'm just gonna do it

595
00:35:31,235 --> 00:35:32,996
and it doesn't take any of my time, bang.

596
00:35:33,997 --> 00:35:35,398
That's the sort of thing that I'm talking about.

597
00:35:36,659 --> 00:35:37,880
Another thing is discovery,

598
00:35:37,980 --> 00:35:39,161
and please don't laugh at my picture,

599
00:35:39,221 --> 00:35:40,682
try to find a good picture for discovery.

600
00:35:42,744 --> 00:35:44,825
Surprise, asparagus, he discovered that.

601
00:35:46,106 --> 00:35:51,350
Discovery is a necessary evil when it comes to design,

602
00:35:51,691 --> 00:35:52,892
and it's not even that evil, right?

603
00:35:53,392 --> 00:35:55,734
We're trying to mine the goodness,

604
00:35:55,874 --> 00:35:56,735
wherever we can find it.

605
00:35:58,916 --> 00:35:59,096
But...

606
00:36:00,763 --> 00:36:04,066
this can lead to some pretty hairy changes in the code,

607
00:36:04,406 --> 00:36:05,386
especially big changes.

608
00:36:05,907 --> 00:36:11,370
If you can try and work hard to find the big changes early on,

609
00:36:11,710 --> 00:36:13,912
obviously that's ideal, but that's not always the case.

610
00:36:14,472 --> 00:36:17,414
So when you come to the programmers with big changes,

611
00:36:18,094 --> 00:36:22,177
obviously this is a time for potential strife.

612
00:36:22,978 --> 00:36:26,180
And if you come to them with a foisting sort of situation,

613
00:36:26,860 --> 00:36:28,121
that's obviously where there's problems.

614
00:36:28,161 --> 00:36:30,162
But if you come to it as a negotiation...

615
00:36:30,869 --> 00:36:33,271
Hey, remember what we said before?

616
00:36:33,291 --> 00:36:34,872
We have to take that back.

617
00:36:35,333 --> 00:36:38,015
But we're willing to negotiate on this and this.

618
00:36:39,196 --> 00:36:44,481
It makes it less about accept this and don't talk back.

619
00:36:45,022 --> 00:36:47,384
As opposed to, we understand there's a partnership.

620
00:36:47,444 --> 00:36:52,488
We understand that we've had to come back on part of what we said before to be a true statement.

621
00:36:52,789 --> 00:36:55,271
And we're willing to work with each other on it.

622
00:36:56,198 --> 00:37:01,881
Reprioritization is a little bit of, oh, that shouldn't have come up. Oh, never mind. Reprioritization

623
00:37:02,322 --> 00:37:07,265
is a lesser evil. I mean, reprioritization might just be there's a demo coming up or

624
00:37:07,285 --> 00:37:10,927
somebody needs to see something or maybe an artist needs something quicker because of

625
00:37:10,947 --> 00:37:16,170
whatever. And so, these are a lot easier to sort of get into the system. But still, again,

626
00:37:16,250 --> 00:37:21,173
try to do it as quick as possible because you don't want to waste work, obviously. Crunch,

627
00:37:21,513 --> 00:37:22,434
everybody's on tiptoes.

628
00:37:25,220 --> 00:37:31,722
When you have people that aren't socially gifted, crunch period suddenly becomes a really hard place.

629
00:37:32,843 --> 00:37:42,086
So, I don't really want to go into this too much, but just remind yourself that again, you're dealing with the can and the banana.

630
00:37:43,147 --> 00:37:46,508
This is the time when the wire might even be a little bit frayed, right?

631
00:37:46,968 --> 00:37:53,511
You have to come at these sort of communications knowing that there's a big gulf to be done here.

632
00:37:54,318 --> 00:37:55,979
And these trouble spots are really about trust.

633
00:37:56,379 --> 00:37:58,900
This is the trust part of the relationship.

634
00:38:00,301 --> 00:38:03,302
The workflow, like I said, sort of slowly erodes trust over

635
00:38:03,362 --> 00:38:06,744
time, because the tool doesn't really do what I want.

636
00:38:06,784 --> 00:38:08,945
And if I ask him, he's not going to really do what I want.

637
00:38:08,985 --> 00:38:10,886
And I'm going to have just more hassles.

638
00:38:11,306 --> 00:38:15,428
And discovery, again, you're dealing with the contract

639
00:38:15,708 --> 00:38:18,749
between design and programming at this point.

640
00:38:19,309 --> 00:38:20,410
And the contract.

641
00:38:21,045 --> 00:38:25,428
Part of the problem that I see with this particular grouping is that the contract is a little

642
00:38:25,488 --> 00:38:26,749
bit inconsistent.

643
00:38:27,730 --> 00:38:33,613
Programmers agree on a contract and they actually have to write that contract into code.

644
00:38:34,474 --> 00:38:36,335
It's somewhat calcified for them.

645
00:38:37,256 --> 00:38:41,778
Design doesn't exactly have that same level of calcification.

646
00:38:42,259 --> 00:38:48,343
They can feel a little bit looser with their contract and they have a little bit of an

647
00:38:48,423 --> 00:38:49,643
easier time to kind of...

648
00:38:51,370 --> 00:38:56,013
change their contract. Whereas, changes to the programmer's side of the contract are

649
00:38:56,073 --> 00:39:04,540
actually somewhat harsh. And this inconsistency, I think, is part of the rub. So, finally,

650
00:39:04,560 --> 00:39:10,744
I want to talk about some bridge methods that are starting to appear in the industry. I

651
00:39:10,804 --> 00:39:16,689
specifically use a rope bridge on this because it's serviceable, but there are some hazards,

652
00:39:16,889 --> 00:39:17,710
and you have to watch out.

653
00:39:18,275 --> 00:39:21,317
and one person with a big knife can kind of cut it all apart.

654
00:39:23,559 --> 00:39:24,880
So first is a technical designer.

655
00:39:25,281 --> 00:39:29,444
This is a person that's gone either direction, right?

656
00:39:29,464 --> 00:39:35,169
You either have a designer who has a lot of programming skill

657
00:39:35,710 --> 00:39:43,956
or a programmer that's decided that he wants to go more into the design direction.

658
00:39:43,996 --> 00:39:44,737
And in either case...

659
00:39:45,333 --> 00:39:50,996
What you really have here is somebody who speaks sort of both languages and they're down on the worker side.

660
00:39:51,456 --> 00:39:57,359
And these guys can be amazingly effective at what they do, at not only bridging the gap between staff,

661
00:39:57,679 --> 00:40:07,564
but also by potentially not being seen by the other members of their team as being,

662
00:40:07,884 --> 00:40:11,866
the programmer is telling me to do this or the designer is demanding this.

663
00:40:12,493 --> 00:40:16,315
they can soften the blow by knowing the language a little bit better of both sides.

664
00:40:16,975 --> 00:40:20,536
However, there's definitely some issues.

665
00:40:20,977 --> 00:40:23,398
They need twice the mentoring and twice the management.

666
00:40:24,018 --> 00:40:26,899
They technically are both a programmer and a designer

667
00:40:26,979 --> 00:40:31,941
and if they're not getting both mentoring and both management,

668
00:40:32,242 --> 00:40:35,523
you can run into some of the problems that you can with green programmers.

669
00:40:36,023 --> 00:40:37,484
And the thing that we all know,

670
00:40:38,604 --> 00:40:42,006
green programmers can cause some severe havoc in a code base.

671
00:40:44,009 --> 00:40:47,492
They can check things in that maybe aren't approved and come in on a weekend with a great

672
00:40:47,572 --> 00:40:50,633
idea and just hack it together.

673
00:40:51,274 --> 00:40:54,436
Stick it in the game, thinking that everything is going to be great.

674
00:40:55,917 --> 00:41:00,720
We don't like this even when the programmers do it, and we certainly don't want anybody

675
00:41:00,800 --> 00:41:03,741
else doing it, especially somebody that's supposed to be there to help us.

676
00:41:04,882 --> 00:41:09,925
All of these sorts of things, and it's not just sort of rogue behavior.

677
00:41:09,945 --> 00:41:11,206
It's also just...

678
00:41:12,417 --> 00:41:17,939
inexperienced programmer things like poorly optimized code or potentially hackable code

679
00:41:18,480 --> 00:41:24,042
on an online game. Things you have to think about. Also again, you have to take care when

680
00:41:24,082 --> 00:41:29,944
you do have designers and programmers and technical designers involved because the tasking

681
00:41:29,984 --> 00:41:34,466
they might feel like somebody's stealing something from somebody. But they might not know who's

682
00:41:35,526 --> 00:41:39,288
supposed to take a particular thing. And so there's a little bit of tap dancing when you're

683
00:41:39,308 --> 00:41:39,728
dealing with

684
00:41:40,407 --> 00:41:43,187
with cross-disciplinary groups simply because of that.

685
00:41:44,267 --> 00:41:46,768
I also don't think that technical designers should be the main designer.

686
00:41:48,008 --> 00:41:53,190
I think that the main designer should have only the player's needs in mind.

687
00:41:53,670 --> 00:41:55,150
He should be the advocate for the player.

688
00:41:55,670 --> 00:42:02,932
And technical designers, whether they want to or not, are also worried about the performance

689
00:42:03,012 --> 00:42:05,692
and the maintainability of some of their stuff.

690
00:42:05,853 --> 00:42:07,313
And that's good.

691
00:42:07,333 --> 00:42:08,253
That's what we want.

692
00:42:10,194 --> 00:42:14,176
causes them to be a little bit more pointed in that direction.

693
00:42:14,196 --> 00:42:18,439
I also think that cross-disciplinary stuff is absolutely the future of some of these

694
00:42:18,479 --> 00:42:24,802
features. We just can't have people that don't have both of these things. The art world has

695
00:42:24,923 --> 00:42:29,885
already embraced this directly with technical artists who can code shaders to make special

696
00:42:29,925 --> 00:42:33,027
effects that are in every game out there, just about.

697
00:42:36,356 --> 00:42:39,097
We're a little bit behind them, but that's the way of it.

698
00:42:40,017 --> 00:42:40,737
But only sort of.

699
00:42:41,097 --> 00:42:43,818
Obviously, you have to deal with some of these issues.

700
00:42:44,318 --> 00:42:49,419
And it's also going to be a culture thing as far as the corporations themselves.

701
00:42:49,520 --> 00:42:53,941
Right now, there is the big three of career tracks.

702
00:42:54,421 --> 00:42:58,282
And people that straddle the fence can sometimes have a hard time getting promoted

703
00:42:58,342 --> 00:43:03,703
because if they don't have two managers that know everything they're doing in an effective way,

704
00:43:03,723 --> 00:43:05,103
it's going to be hard for them to get promoted.

705
00:43:05,834 --> 00:43:11,078
a design manager, let's say, with a technical designer to really know just how much value

